Taiwan's most valuable company said that new gadget launches  in the second half, particularly smartphones, will help boost  its revenue for the quarter ending in September by at least 15  percent versus the June quarter, which suffered from the  appreciation of the Taiwanese currency against the U.S. dollar.  TSMC, which has a market capitalisation that exceeds Intel  Corp's, said revenue for the July-September quarter  will be between $8.12 billion and $8.22 billion, compared to the  $7.06 billion posted for the April-June quarter.
title: TSMC guides Q3 revenue higher, but wary of currency blows

summary: Taiwan Semiconductor  Manufacturing Co, the world's largest contract  chipmaker and a major supplier to Apple Inc, said its  second-quarter net profit fell 8.6 percent from the same period  a year ago as revenue also fell slightly.  Net profit was T$66.27 billion ($2.19 billion) for the  April-June period, down from T$72.51 billion in the year-ago  quarter.  TSMC's revenue in the quarter fell 3.6 percent from the same  period a year ago and was off 8.6 percent from the first quarter  of this year.
title: TSMC posts 8.6 pct y/y fall in Q2 net profit to T$66.27 bln

summary: The venerable semiconductor newsletter Microprocessor Report today describes how Intel's (INTC) manufacturing “roadmap” for its chips is becoming more complex: the company still clearly leads the competition, but it must also be more selective than in years past about how and when it uses that lead.  "Previously, Intel’s manufacturing strategy was a club with which it could bludgeon competitors,” writes the Report’s David Kanter.  Kanter writes that Intel correctly dismissed the various technical claims to leadership of Samsung Electronics (005930KS) and Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing (TSM), which claim to have a “10-nanometer” technology for chips that is ahead of Intel’s “14-nanometer” Intel accurately points out such claims by the two competitors are somewhat disingenuous, writes Kanter.
title: Intel Trades 'Club' for 'Scalpel,' Says Microprocessor Report

summary: Taiwan Semiconductor  Manufacturing Co, the world's largest contract  chipmaker and a major supplier to Apple Inc, said its  quarterly profits were hit by a strong local currency and  cautioned it expected this trend to continue.  Taiwan's exporters have been hurt by the strong currency,  which is the third best performing currency in Asia so far this  year, just behind the South Korean won and the Indian rupee.  TSMC expects the Taiwan dollar to appreciate by 2.1  percent in the second quarter, dragging its revenue down by the  same rate over the period and reducing its gross margin and  operating margin by about 85 basis points, Chief Financial  Officer Lora Ho said at an earnings conference on Thursday.
title: TSMC's Q1 profits hurt by strong Taiwan dollar; cautions trend to stay

summary: Intel (INTC) shares are up 5 cents at $35.65 after the company yesterday held an event in San Francisco to talk about its manufacturing prowess.  One of the main takeaways for the Street, both bull and bear, from yesterday's event is that the company is signaling an intention to be more aggressive in taking contract manufacturing of chips — known as "foundry" — than it has been in past.  Instinet's Romit Shah, who has a Buy rating on Intel stock, and a $40 price target, writes that the company succeeded in showing it is ahead of competitors such as Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing (TSM) in critical aspects of transistors:  Intel showed that its 10nm process has the tightest transistor and metal pitches in the industry along with hyper scale features for leadership density.

summary: [at Barrons.com] - Citigroup chip analysts Roland Shu Christopher Danely today review the prospect of Intel (INTC) competing directly with Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing (TSM) in building chips for other companies, and declare TSM the likely winner in any such face-off. You’ll recall Intel during its annual Developer Forum in August said it had struck a partnership with ARM Holdings to provide “foundry” services to chip designers licensing ARM’s chip technology, opening a door to making a much broader set of parts for a much broader set of third parties than Intel has ever courted. The vast majority of processors in everything from autos to mobile devices to servers use circuitry based on ARM's designs, not the designs of Intel, so this expands Intel's market beyond its own designs.
title: Intel a Year Behind TSM in Foundry Capabilities, Says Citi

Taiwan previously controlled such hi-tech investment on fears the island could lose its competitive edge to China, which still regards Taiwan as part of its territory awaiting reunification -- by force if necessary. China, a huge consumer of electronics, is of growing importance to the semiconductor industry and TSMC faces intense competition from regional rivals, such as Samsung, as well as slowing global demand in the technology sector.
